{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/string-functions-in-sql-9f08fabfa60e", "time": 1683003972.978781, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/string-functions-in-sql-9f08fabfa60e/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "String Functions in SQL. There\u2019s far more to analysing strings\u2026 | by Robert de Graaf | Towards Data Science", "h1": "String Functions in SQL", "description": "Although SQL sometimes has a \u2018perpetual bridesmaid\u2019 reputation next to more richly featured analytics environments, such as R or Python with their richly featured libraries, in the last few years the\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.amazon.com/Managing-Your-Data-Science-Projects/dp/1484249062/ref=pd_rhf_ee_p_img_1?_encoding=UTF8&psc=1&refRID=4X4S14FQEBKHZSDYYMZY", "anchor_text": "Managing Your Data Science Projects", "paragraph_index": 11}], "all_paragraphs": ["Although SQL sometimes has a \u2018perpetual bridesmaid\u2019 reputation next to more richly featured analytics environments, such as R or Python with their richly featured libraries, in the last few years the increased adoption of standard functions for dealing with strings has strongly increased the range of possibilities for dealing with strings in SQL.", "TRANSLATE and REPLACE are two more functions which are available in many database systems. They\u2019ve been around for many years, but some databases like SQL Server only added them comparatively recently; MySQL is still yet to add TRANSLATE.", "Both of these functions serve to replace strings. REPLACE replaces a whole string with another string, while TRANSLATE exchanges one character at a time.", "Therefore, you could use REPLACE like this, to replace a whole name or word with another whole name or word:", "On the other, as TRANSLATE replaces characters with other specific characters, making it useful for overcoming repeatable problems in the data. For example, it\u2019s a good function to use if a small number of alpha or symbol characters have become mixed in with numeric data, preventing them being properly treated as numbers \u2014 just use translate to remove those characters. Another use is if there are commas being used in text data within a table you want to export as a csv. If you let the commas remain and try to export, there\u2019s a good chance that the columns won\u2019t be detected correctly \u2014 new columns will be inserted where they shouldn\u2019t be.", "For example, imagine a list of country names, where, for example, North Korea, is listed as \u2018Korea, Democratic People\u2019s Republic of\u2019 and China is listed as \u2018China, People\u2019s Republic of\u2019 \u2014 their official names in English presented to enable them to indexed under Korea and China.", "If you leave the commas in, the country name column will sometimes be split, ruining the correspondence of columns to data. Therefore you want to remove the commas. Try the following:", "The trick with the TRANSLATE function is that the list of characters that are to be replaced and the list that will replace them need to be in the same order so that SQL knows what to do with them. Overall, however, this is a very flexible function.", "Another major function that has been introduced to the standard in recent years is the LISTAGG function. This function is also found in SQL Server with similar syntax as STRING_AGG. This function concatenates the string values of different cells in a column into a single string, with a separator specified by the user.", "One way that you can use this function is if you store name and address data in component form \u2014 a separate column for first name, last name, house number, street name etc \u2014 which can make doing searches on specific attributes easier, you can then combine the components into the whole name and address, with your preferred format. Try the following:", "It may often seem difficult to know how to approach strings in SQL. However, this is in big part because the functions which are there to help you tackle strings the right way are not as well known as they ought to be. Mastering the functions discussed above will give you extra flexibility to tackle strings.", "Robert de Graaf\u2019s book, Managing Your Data Science Projects, is out now through Apress.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F9f08fabfa60e&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fstring-functions-in-sql-9f08fabfa60e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fstring-functions-in-sql-9f08fabfa60e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fstring-functions-in-sql-9f08fabfa60e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fstring-functions-in-sql-9f08